1 Results

Figure 1.1: Compositional variance explained in first two PC axes for each metabarcoding dataset.

Aside from compositional variance in datasets testing the temporal differences (test 2) the pattern of variance explained for the first two PCs in each dataset was consistent with non-rarefied analyses.

1.1 Intensified Harvesting

1.1.1 Differences in diversity

Figure 1.2: Difference in diversity (richness, inverse Simpsons or Shannon) based on orthogonal contrasts defined in Table ?? (TR = harvested vs uncut, FFR = forest floor removal, BGBR = below-ground biomass removal, BRt = biomass retention). Significance is indicated with colour (darker are more significant) and shape (triangles are significant at p < 0.05 and circles are not significant at p < 0.05. Values higher than zero indicate there was an increase in diversity from the treatment, values lower than zero indicate there was a decrease in diversity from the treatment.

Largely, diversity metrics did not differ across the various harvesting treatments, compared to full tree harvesting. Rarefied datasets had some differences from non-rarefied analyses: Inverse Simpson and Shannon diversity in bacterial communities were significantly increased with forest floor removal, and Shannon diversity was significantly decreased by below-ground biomass removal. Responses of ITS richness and Inverse Simpsons diversity were also changed, where there were significant impacts of biomass intensification (BRt), but the previously detected significant differences due to forest floor removal were lost.

Betadispersion

Figure 1.4: Results of betadispersion tests comparing community structures of the different harvesting treatments. The betadispersion of each treatment is shown on the y axis, and the treatment is shown along the x axis. Significant contrast tests as outlined in Table ?? (TR = harvested vs uncut, FFR = forest floor removal, BGBR = below-ground biomass removal, BRt = biomass retention) are indicated along the top of the figure with lines and symbols designating test significance (* = p < 0.05, ** = p < 0.01, *** = p < 0.001).

Community differences in rarefied datasets had similar amounts of variance explained by harvesting, stump removal, below-ground biomass removal and forest floor removal compared to unrarefied datasets.

1.1.3 Compositional RDA plots

Explained Variance in RDAs

Figure 1.5: Proportion of community structural variance explained by RDA axes constrained by the harvesting treatments. Model names are described as the targeted gene (16S, 18S, ITS, or, F230), summarization level (ESV, genus, or functional groupings) and the soil layers represented in the rda model (MIN = 0-10 cm depth mineral soil samples, LFH = L, FH, or LFH samples).

Bacterial (16S)

Fungal (ITS)

Arthropods (F230)

Eukaryotes (18S)

The RDA axes associated with Unharvested and Bladed treatments explained more variance (0.132 - 0.274) than other axes, these differences were confirmed by the significantly different compositions of Bladed and Unharvested treatments from Full-tree harvesting found in PERMANOVA. The remaining RDA axes associated with Stumped and Stem Only treatments explained smaller amounts of variance (0.037 - 0.095). Stumped treatments were significantly different from full-tree harvesting, but there was no significant difference between stem only and full tree harvesting.

The ESVs that had significant compositional differences were largely identified as the same phylogenetic groups that were detected in non-rarefied analyses. However, several Bacterial ESVs with different identifications were identified in the rarefied analyses (i.e., Acidibacter, Povalibacter, Athalassotoga, Aliidongia, Mycobacterium, Caballeronia, Rhodoplanes, Pseudorhodoplanes, Bradyrhizobium). Rarefied fungal (ITS) communities also had some significant changes to ESVs identified to phylogenetic groups that were not detected in nonrarefied communities (i.e., Oidiodendron, Piloderma, Umbelopsis, Hygrophorus, Trichomaceae, Phialocephela, Pyronemataceae, Rhizoscyphus, Ophiocordyceps). There were two ESVs detected at a Benjamini-Hochberg corrected p-value of 0.05, while none were detected at that level of significance in the non-rarefied dataset, with the two genus that were detected being detected at p = 0.05 in the non-rarefied dataset. There were only three ESVs in rarefied data from phylogenetic groups that were not detected in nonrarefied 18S communities, (Athelia, Archaeperidinium).

The eukaryotic groups that were identified generally support non-rarefied results, that forest floor removal generally selects for organisms more adapted to harsher conditions or grasses/meadow species (e.g., Trichomaceae, Acidibacter, Athalassotoga, Odiodendron, Rhizoscyphus) and harvesting generally changes community structure by reducing mycorrhizae and encouraging saprotrophy (e.g., higher Piloderma).

1.2 Topographic differences

1.2.1 Differences in diversity

Figure 1.6: Orthogonal contrasts between microtopography features as described in Table ?? (T.B = Trench vs Bladed, T.PF = Trench vs Piles and Flats, P.F = Piles vs Flats). Values lower than zero indicate the first term in the contrast is lower in diversity, values higher than zero indicate the first term in the contrast has higher diversity as an effect.

Generally, though the magnitude of differences changed, tests performed on rarefied diversity metrics supported the results of the non-rarefied analyses. Bacterial Shannon and Simpsons diversities gained significance after rarefying for Trench-Bladed comparisons, and Forest Floor removal comparisons, but lost significance for the forest floor removal effect in Eukaryotic 18S communities. The pattern of responses were mostly the same in direction, with the exception of Bacterial 16S Simpsons diversity, which gained effects.

Betadispersion

Figure 1.8: Results of orthogonal betadispersion tests comparing community structures of the different microtopography features on full-tree sites, tests are outlined in Table 2. The betadispersion of each treatment (R2) is shown on the y axis, and the treatment is shown along the x-axis. Significant differences are indicated in red text (* = p < 0.05, ** = p < 0.01, *** = p < 0.001). A. Bacterial 16S, B. Fungal ITS, C. Arthropod F230, D. Eukaryotic 18S.

There was much more overlap between Trench and Bladed communities in rarefied datasets than in non-rarefied analyses. However, this did not eliminate the conclusion that the community assemblages in Trenched and Bladed sites were different. In fact, the results of permanova tests in rarefied and non-rarefied datasets were very similar, with the main differences between the results being generally, a slightly lower amount of explained variance for rarefied tests versus their unrarefied equivalent.

1.2.3 Compositional RDA plots

Explained Variance in RDAs

Figure 1.9: Proportion of community structural variance explained by RDA axes constrained by microtopography. Model names are described as the targeted gene (16S, 18S, ITS, or, F230), summarization level (ESV, genus, or functional groupings) and the soil layers represented in the rda model (MIN = 0-10 cm depth mineral soil samples, LFH = L, FH, or LFH samples).

Bacterial (16S)

Fungal (ITS)

Arthropods (F230)

Eukaryotes (18S)

Across all metabarcoding communities, the RDA axes associated with the most explainable variance were associated with Trench features. The Bacterial community was the most different between trench and flat features, with 20% of the community variance explained by the trench axis. This was consistent with the results from non-rarefied analyses. There was more separation between Flat and Pile sites in the rarefied, versus unrarefied dataset however. Most other RDAs were similar in both amount of variance explained on the axes, and the direction of responses.

There were many bacterial ESVs with significant changes in composition between topographic features in rarefied datasets that were identified to phylogenies that were not found in unrarefied datasets (i.e, Caballeronia, Variibacter, Bradyrhizobium, Paraburkholderia, Rhodoplanes, Pseudorhodoplanes, Acidipila, Rosearcus). Rarefying of ITS communities detected Heliotales and Cadophora ESVS that had similar compositions across sites to the unrarefied datasets, and detected differences in two ESVs identified as Agaricomycetes and Mortierella which were not detected in unrarafied datasets. All of the phylogenic groups of ESVs with significantly changed compositional abundance (p <0.05) in F230 communities were detected in the unrarefied communities. Compositional abundance of 18S ESVs from rarefied analyses had ESVs that were identified as phylogenies that were not present in unrarefied datasets (Polytrichum, Rosulabryum, Archaeperidinium, Limnognathia).

These groups consisted of generalist chemoheterotrophic fungi that could be decomposing wood or associated with plants being increased in flats and piles (e.g., Paraburkholderia, Mortierella), and organisms that are more associated with living in environments with high temperatures or nutrient limitations (e.g., Acidipila).

1.3 Seasonal Patterns

1.3.1 Differences in diversity

Figure 1.10: Diversity (Shannon, Inverse Simpsons, and ESV richness) for each metabarcode target (Bacterial 16S and Fungal ITS2) across three months of sampling for full tree and unharvested treatments. Unharvested is shown in green, and full tree is displayed in blue.

Just as in unrarefied datasets, while community compositions had responses to harvesting and season, there were no differences in the seasonal responses related to harvesting. There were increased inverse simpsons diversity metrics in rarefied bacterial communities, but decreased inverse Simpsons diversity in Eukaryotic 18S sequences. The pattern and magnitudes of Shannon and richness across samples were very similar between rarefied and non-rarefied datasets, through richnesses were lower in rarefied datsets.

PERMANOVA results

Figure 1.11: Results of PERMANOVA tests comparing community structures of months (J = June, A = August, O = October) within full tree and unharvested treatments. A) Results of interaction of months and harvest treatments. B) Results of pairwise comparisons. The variance explained by each comparison or model parameter (R2) is shown on the x axis, and the probability of the effect is along the y axis (Pr (>F)). A black line is used to represent p = 0.05.

Betadispersion

Figure 1.12: Results of pairwise betadispersion tests comparing community structures of months within full tree and unharvested treatments. The betadispersion of each treatment (R2) is shown on the y axis, and the treatment is shown along the x-axis. Significant contrasts are indicated at the top of the graph with colour to indicate whether they are harvested or unharvested and significance levels supplied symbolically (* = p < 0.05, ** = p < 0.01, *** = p < 0.001).

Community compositional differences were also highly similar between both rarefied and non-rarefied analyses. The only notable differences in beta diversity tests would be lower amounts of variance explained in rarefied analyses, and one less test found significant at p = 0.05 (Full-tree june/october differences). Betadispersion had no significant differences in rarefied datasets, while there were some differences in full tree datasets of unrarefied analyses.

RDAs of rarefied datasets and unrarefied datasets were both low (less than 10% of variance explained by seasonal variation). Seasonal impacts on both Unharvested and Harvested treatments were very similar in rarefied an unrarefied analyses. There were no changes to the conclusions made from the unrarefied analyses.

Bacterial ESV with significant changes in rarefied datasets did not have strong, clear trends of seasonal change, with seasonal patterns being much less clear than those observed for bacterial ESV in unrarefied datasets. Across the remaining datasets, detected effects were mostly related to harvest treatment differences, not seasonal differences, in both rarefied and unrarefied analyses. All of the phylogenetic groups identified in rarefied 16S ITS, and F230 datasets were also found in unrarefied analyses. There was only one group that was detected in rarefied analyses of 18S communities that was not detected in the unrarefied analyses.
